               <p>1339. <persName id="def1-1339-18420404" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1339-18420404" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1339-18420404" type="surname" value="STARR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1339-18420404" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">EDWARD STARR</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted for<rs id="t18420404-1339-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420404-1339-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420404-1339-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> stealing, on the <rs id="t18420404-cd-191" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420404-1339-offence-1 t18420404-cd-191"></join>5th of April</rs>, at <placeName id="t18420404-geo-20">
                        <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420404-1339-offence-1 t18420404-geo-20"></join>Enfield</placeName>, 4 bushels of a certain mixture consisting of oats, beans, and chaff, value 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18420404-name-1125" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1125" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1125" type="surname" value="MOUNTAIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1125" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420404-1339-offence-1 t18420404-name-1125"></join>Peter Mountain</persName>; and</rs>
                  <persName id="def2-1339-18420404" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1339-18420404" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1339-18420404" type="surname" value="HALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1339-18420404" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN HALL</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18420404-1339-offence-2" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420404-1339-offence-2" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420404-1339-offence-2" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp>, for feloniously receiving, harbouring, assisting, and maintaining the said <persName id="t18420404-name-1127" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1127" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1127" type="surname" value="STARR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1127" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420404-1339-offence-2 t18420404-name-1127"></join>Edward Starr</persName>, well knowing him to have committed the said felony.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420404-name-1128" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1128" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1128" type="surname" value="MOUNTAIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1128" type="given" value="PETER"></interp>PETER MOUNTAIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a coach-master, and carry on business, amongst other places, at the Saracen's Head, Snow-hill—I send corn down to Waltham-cross and other places for horses. I have employed Starr to carry it down for the last two years—in consequence of suspicion I enter<lb></lb>tained before, I on this occasion mixed with my corn some pieces of pa<lb></lb>per, to enable me to identify it—on Tuesday, the 5th of April, ten sacks of corn were delivered to Starr, he was to take seven to Waltham-cross, and leave three at Wade's-mill—I have since seen some corn found by the police<lb></lb>man—it is a portion of what was in the seven sacks for Waltham-cross—I had torn the pieces of paper and put them in myself—I had observed my horses were thinner than they ought to be, and was obliged to have extra horses to do the work.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> YOU had employed him about two years? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, occasionally—he was not in my regular employ<lb></lb>ment—he brought hay and straw to London—I used to pay him so much for each job.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420404-name-1129" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1129" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1129" type="surname" value="SINCLAIR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420404-name-1129" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD SINCLAIR</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. In consequence of informa<lb></lb>tion I received, I stationed myself near Mr. Dyson's stable, at Waltham-cross on Wednesday, the 6th of April, and between seven and eight o'clock in the morning I saw Starr draw his cart into Mr. Dyson's stable, were Mr. Mountain's horses stand—he got into the cart, and gave Hall out two full sacks, which he took into the stable—he then gave him out a</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184204040192"></xptr>
               <p>third full sack, which he took into the loft, and while he was gone with out that sack, Starr threw an empty sack into the stable—he then gave him out three more full sacks, which he took into the loft—Starr then got out of the cart, and went into the loft where Hall was—Winsbury was with me—Hall and Starr came out of the loft, and went into the stable—they were in there some time—Starr came out and drew his cart out of the yard—we followed and took him into custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was the empty sack put with the full sacks in the stable? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—the sacks were all shot when I got into the stable, but he had only delivered six full ones to Hall—I found all the seven empty sacks together—after taking Starr to the station, I went back to the stable, and found Hall there—I asked him how many sacks of corn he had received of Starr on account of Mr. Mountain—he said seven—I asked where he shot them—he said, "Two and a half in here below," meaning the stable, "and four and a half in the loft"—I took him into custody—we went to Starr's house, at Enfield, searched, and found some corn there—his house is two miles on the London side of the road to Waltham-cross—we brought away between two and three bushels of corn from there, and found the papers, which were recognized by Mr. Mountain, amongst the corn found in the bin in Starr's stable.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PHILLIPS</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did Mr. Mountain know the corn at once? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> His foreman did.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Starr's Defence.</hi> I never had a grain of Mr. Mountain's corn in my life.</p>
               <p>(Starr received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">STARR—
